---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { STORM_DOOR_URL } from '../consts';
---
<Base
  title="About Jonathan Sexton — In the Wld"
  description="Jonathan Sexton is a writer and musician from East Tennessee, born fifty-five days after MTV launched. He is writing The Sound of Something More."
  nav="solid"
>
  <div class="pagehead">
    <p class="kicker">Who is writing</p>
    <h1>Jonathan Sexton</h1>
    <p class="standfirst">One foot in the holler, one in tomorrow.</p>
  </div>

  <article class="read">
    <div class="col reveal">
      <img src="/assets/portrait.jpg" alt="Jonathan Sexton seated on a red couch in a wood-paneled room, a lamp glowing beside him." width="1000" height="1500" style="border-radius:3px; margin-bottom:2rem; box-shadow:0 24px 60px rgba(57,53,51,0.18)" />

      <p class="lede">When Jonathan Sexton looks in the mirror, he still sees the songwriter first. He was raised by parents whose first date was a Charlie Daniels Band concert, in the same East Tennessee mountains that gave us Dolly Parton, surrounded by the stories and songs that would shape how he sees the world. His father started filling his head with liner notes before he could read. Who played on what, who produced which records, who really wrote that song. All of it turned out to be his richest inheritance.</p>

      <p>His path reads like a choose-your-own-adventure. Public school teacher, then professional touring musician. A Bonnaroo stage, an MTV O Music Award, a Guinness World Record along the way. He co-founded an Inc. 5000 creative agency, held executive roles in global technology, built music technology platforms, and studied artificial intelligence at MIT. He wrote music and business columns for his hometown paper and cultural commentary for MTV.com. His brain runs like Pop-Up Video, and he is still not ready to say out loud how many songs he pulled off Napster.</p>

      <p>Born in 1981, fifty-five days after MTV launched, he belongs to the bridge generation. The last to call their friends on rotary phones, now raising kids who talk to Alexa like a sibling. After running from the South and going out to see the world, he found his way back to Tennessee with his wife and three sons, still writing songs and fronting his band, because some callings don't clock out at five or after forty.</p>

      <p>Under the mentorship of New York Times bestselling author Kathryn Aalto, he is writing The Sound of Something More, a book arguing that songs belong on a shelf with dreams and prayers, the immeasurable forces most people believe in without being able to prove. In a world of ones and zeros, his work is a reminder that some things still need three chords and the truth.</p>

      <span class="kicker">Reach him</span>
      <p>The nearest door in is <a href={STORM_DOOR_URL} rel="noopener">The Storm Door</a>, the letter that arrives most Saturday mornings. For press and other inquiries, write to <a href="mailto:js@inthewld.com">js@inthewld.com</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
